WEBVTT

00:09.051 --> 00:12.088
ZOE: This place rots.
Stupid, boring,
quiet, boring,

00:12.179 --> 00:16.047
one-horse, boring town.
Why do I have to burn
my Saturday volunteering?

00:16.141 --> 00:17.551
Oh, you're not volunteering.

00:17.643 --> 00:18.678
It's called
community service.

00:18.769 --> 00:20.805
And you wouldn't
be doing it if you didn't
pull the fire alarm

00:20.854 --> 00:22.014
during your |.Q. test.

00:22.064 --> 00:24.350
lwouldn't be doing it
if you hadn't arrested me.

00:24.399 --> 00:27.186
You know, sometimes
it sucks have a dad
who's the town smokey.

00:27.236 --> 00:29.693
Well, sometimes it sucks
having a daughter who's
the town delinquent.

00:32.658 --> 00:33.864
I take it back.

00:34.368 --> 00:35.403
Gee, thanks.

00:35.494 --> 00:37.200
It always sucks.

00:38.038 --> 00:39.574
(LAUGHING)

00:43.669 --> 00:45.910
Please, don't
make me do this.
I hate old people.

00:46.004 --> 00:47.710
You don't do this,
you won't live to be one.

00:47.756 --> 00:48.916
Can't we just
discuss this?

00:49.007 --> 00:50.543
You're going,
end of discussion.

00:52.719 --> 00:53.708
lwill dojail time.

00:53.804 --> 00:55.544
Go. Scoot.

01:01.436 --> 01:02.425
(DOOR CLOSING)

01:03.647 --> 01:06.059
I can't
tell you how much
I appreciate this, sir.

01:06.149 --> 01:08.231
No need
to thank me, Fargo.
You've earned it.

01:08.318 --> 01:11.560
Having your own office
is a right of passage.

01:11.613 --> 01:13.945
It's a symbol
of status and rank.

01:14.157 --> 01:16.409
Tells the world
you've arrived.

01:22.291 --> 01:23.406
(ELEVATOR DOOR OPENING)

01:23.458 --> 01:25.289
Not yet.

01:29.298 --> 01:30.583
Section Five?

01:31.425 --> 01:32.585
Pace yourself.

01:34.094 --> 01:35.254
(BEEPING)

01:40.767 --> 01:41.973
What's down here?

01:42.060 --> 01:44.767
You and your new office.

02:06.209 --> 02:07.494
(KEYS JINGLING)

02:13.592 --> 02:15.503
Congratulations, Fargo.

02:17.012 --> 02:19.503
You deserve
every square foot of it.

02:19.848 --> 02:21.054
Thanks.

02:22.434 --> 02:24.800
What did you do
to get put down here?

02:24.853 --> 02:26.013
I earned it.

02:26.104 --> 02:28.766
Having your own office
is a right of passage.

02:28.815 --> 02:30.601
It's a symbol
of status and rank.

02:30.651 --> 02:33.188
(SCOFFS)
Rank's the word all right.

02:33.278 --> 02:35.189
It smells like
something died in here.

02:35.280 --> 02:38.443
Like, say, the 1970's.

02:38.533 --> 02:40.910
You have no vision.
Once all this junk's gone,

02:40.994 --> 02:42.985
this will be
an exemplary office space.

02:43.080 --> 02:45.492
Just lacking...
A woman's touch?

02:45.582 --> 02:46.571
Style.

02:46.833 --> 02:48.414
Well, you've got a lot
of great stuff in here.

02:48.502 --> 02:50.663
Just, it deserves
our respect.

02:51.505 --> 02:53.496
The dumpster's down the hall
to the left.

02:53.548 --> 02:54.628
Dumpster? No, no, no.

02:54.675 --> 02:56.381
One man's trash
is another man's treasure.

02:56.468 --> 02:57.833
Been nice doing
business with you.

02:59.346 --> 03:01.803
Check this out.

03:02.891 --> 03:05.724
What do you think?
Stereo?

03:06.520 --> 03:09.478
Sure.
First generation iPod.

03:12.025 --> 03:14.562
How do you turn
this thing on?

03:15.696 --> 03:16.685
On?

03:17.280 --> 03:19.191
It's got keyholes.

03:20.367 --> 03:21.903
And we got keys.

03:21.993 --> 03:24.325
I saw some
in the desk over here.

03:28.625 --> 03:30.707
Hey, these two match.

03:32.254 --> 03:33.835
Here. Go unlock your side.

03:38.385 --> 03:41.468
Ready? Set. Go.

03:50.731 --> 03:53.438
Just another old piece
of useless junk.

03:54.025 --> 03:55.731
SPENCER:
That was almost exciting.

03:55.819 --> 03:57.059
(WHIRRING)

03:57.571 --> 04:00.438
(ALARM BLARING)
ELECTRONIC VOICE: Primary
ﬁring sequence initiated.

04:00.532 --> 04:03.695
Weapon will deploy
in 24 hours.

04:04.661 --> 04:07.152
I don't think
I like this station.

04:11.585 --> 04:14.577
Well, car or no car,
it's a 30-mile-an-hour zone.

04:14.629 --> 04:17.757
Don't you have
anything better to do
than harass me?

04:17.799 --> 04:19.915
No. Not really.

04:20.010 --> 04:21.671
(RUMBLING)

04:25.307 --> 04:26.717
Now you do.

04:31.938 --> 04:33.599
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

04:43.283 --> 04:44.784
Yeah, that can't be good.

04:44.826 --> 04:46.362
(CAR ALARM SOUNDING)

05:23.782 --> 05:25.318
TWIN 1:
What's going on, Sheriff?

05:25.367 --> 05:27.198
CARTER: l was hoping
you could tell me.

05:27.285 --> 05:28.741
This sort of
thing happen often?

05:28.829 --> 05:31.241
Not to my recollection.
I've never seen
anything like it.

05:31.331 --> 05:32.832
It's some sort of ICBM.

05:33.166 --> 05:34.747
ICBM? Please.

05:34.835 --> 05:36.120
Look at the circumference.

05:36.169 --> 05:37.875
Clearly that's an IRBM.

05:37.963 --> 05:39.294
So you guys have
seen this before?

05:39.339 --> 05:40.454
Nope.
Nope.

05:41.508 --> 05:43.590
Thanks, guys. Big help.

05:43.677 --> 05:44.837
What do you
think it is, Sheriff?

05:44.928 --> 05:46.759
(CELL PHONE RINGING)
Oh, I know exactly
what it is.

05:46.972 --> 05:48.132
Trouble.

05:49.224 --> 05:51.636
Carter.
ALLISON: It's Allison.
We 've got trouble.

05:51.810 --> 05:55.348
That's exactly
what I said. Trouble.

06:02.404 --> 06:03.814
Well, hello.

06:07.200 --> 06:08.610
Unfortunately.

06:08.702 --> 06:09.942
I've heard
a lot about you.

06:10.036 --> 06:12.573
But everyone deserves
a second chance, right?

06:12.789 --> 06:14.745
Or a third or fourth.

06:15.041 --> 06:16.827
Let's put you
right to work, okay?

06:16.877 --> 06:19.835
Actually, Doris,
see, I usually ease
into my day

06:19.880 --> 06:22.337
with a latte and maybe
some sort of pastry.

06:22.883 --> 06:23.872
Funny.

06:23.967 --> 06:26.549
I understand we have you
for the next 13 Saturdays.

06:26.636 --> 06:27.625
Thirteen?

06:27.971 --> 06:29.836
A hundred hours divided
by eight-hour shifts.

06:29.890 --> 06:33.223
I'm afraid that
three months of Saturdays
is not gonna work for me.

06:33.310 --> 06:36.393
So, why don't you say
we just get the whole thing
over in one fell swoop?

06:36.479 --> 06:38.219
Let's start
with the rec room.

06:38.982 --> 06:41.598
Up and to the side.

06:43.737 --> 06:45.853
WOMAN: Wide circles forward.

06:46.281 --> 06:47.817
Holy crap.

06:47.908 --> 06:49.773
This is the rec room?

06:51.745 --> 06:53.326
It's a nice place to die.

06:53.413 --> 06:55.404
Even nicer place to live.

06:55.749 --> 06:57.910
The residents of Eureka
give so much.

06:58.001 --> 07:00.663
This facility is
our way to give back.

07:04.466 --> 07:06.798
Run out of tennis balls?

07:07.385 --> 07:11.344
I guess all the massages
in the world can't stop you
from losing your mind.

07:11.890 --> 07:12.879
Here.

07:18.772 --> 07:20.433
ANNOUNCER: And deuce.

07:25.195 --> 07:26.230
(CROWD GASPING)

07:31.409 --> 07:35.243
So, Doris, are there
any age restrictions
on getting a room here?

07:35.288 --> 07:36.323
(CHUCKLING)

07:36.414 --> 07:38.905
You've got a darling
sense of humor.

07:39.459 --> 07:42.041
Come on.
| assigned you to Eugenia.

07:43.797 --> 07:45.958
Eugenia, this is Zoe.

07:46.007 --> 07:47.998
She's going to
assist you today.

07:48.093 --> 07:52.336
lfl desired assistants,
I'd be living in
an assisted living facility.

07:52.639 --> 07:55.176
Don't mind her.
She has teence
of an attitude problem.

07:55.266 --> 07:56.972
I do not.
I do not.

07:57.227 --> 07:59.718
Oh, you two should
get on just fine.

08:03.191 --> 08:04.977
You smoke?
No.

08:05.068 --> 08:06.057
Drink?
No.

08:06.152 --> 08:07.141
You lying?

08:07.362 --> 08:08.351
Maybe.

08:09.364 --> 08:11.480
What kind of a name
is Zoe anyway?

08:11.574 --> 08:13.110
It's a popular one.

08:13.159 --> 08:14.319
You know,
probably as popular

08:14.369 --> 08:17.486
as Eugenia was back
in the Great Depression.

08:18.331 --> 08:20.993
For once, Doris maybe right.

08:22.502 --> 08:23.833
How's my hair?

08:24.129 --> 08:25.665
Your hair? Oh, it's fine.

08:25.755 --> 08:27.336
How's my hair?
Wait, why are we whispering?

08:27.424 --> 08:32.134
But what matters most
is the matter of how
we handle antimatter.

08:32.345 --> 08:33.460
That used to be me.

08:33.596 --> 08:36.463
Antimatter, unlike matter...

08:36.516 --> 08:37.756
You used to talk to yourself?

08:37.851 --> 08:38.840
No.

08:39.227 --> 08:41.218
He used to talk to me.

08:46.943 --> 08:49.025
It had to come
from somewhere.

08:49.112 --> 08:50.773
Keep looking.
MAN: Yes, sir, Dr. Stark.

08:50.864 --> 08:53.230
Allison,
glad to see you.
Shenﬁ.

08:54.701 --> 08:55.736
Scientist.

08:55.827 --> 08:57.067
Which one of your guys
is responsible

08:57.162 --> 08:59.574
for the Cuban
Missile Crisis popping up
all over town?

08:59.664 --> 09:01.450
They're not missiles.

09:01.624 --> 09:02.659
Really?

09:02.709 --> 09:04.700
Because I have a town
full of extremely
anxious people

09:04.794 --> 09:06.250
who think they look a lot
like missiles.

09:06.337 --> 09:09.249
What are they, Nathan?
And why do they look
a lot like missiles?

09:09.340 --> 09:11.080
We're working on it.

09:11.509 --> 09:13.716
So, you don't know?
He doesn't know.

09:13.803 --> 09:15.384
Don't touch the buttons.

09:15.472 --> 09:17.087
l have to call this in
to the DOD.

09:17.182 --> 09:19.423
Not yet.
We have plenty of time
to figure this out.

09:19.517 --> 09:22.099
Well, I can only wait
so long and I'll need
to have answers.

09:22.187 --> 09:24.052
Like what are these
things that look a lot
like missiles,

09:24.147 --> 09:25.478
but aren't,
popping up all over

09:25.565 --> 09:26.725
your top-secret
little town?

09:28.860 --> 09:30.066
Give us a little room,
people.

09:30.153 --> 09:32.064
Sorry, but Henry's
a lot smarter and faster
than me...

09:32.155 --> 09:34.737
Fargo, Fargo,
it's the best decision
you made all day. Henry?

09:34.783 --> 09:36.774
Well, it's definitely
a weapon and this machine
controls it.

09:36.868 --> 09:40.235
Well, tell me more than that.
It's set to discharge a huge
ionosphere particle beam.

09:40.330 --> 09:41.570
FARGO: Oh, jeez.
Okay, okay,

09:41.664 --> 09:44.952
this ion beam thingy
is what exactly?

09:45.043 --> 09:47.830
Irradiated uranium isotopes.
Oh, God.

09:52.759 --> 09:54.340
I've searched
your entire database.

09:54.427 --> 09:56.008
There's not one
single record of silos,

09:56.096 --> 09:58.929
or irradiated isotopes,
or ionosphere particle beams.

09:59.015 --> 10:00.050
Try death ray?

10:00.100 --> 10:02.386
It's as if the machine
never existed.

10:03.061 --> 10:04.346
Did you try turning it off?

10:05.522 --> 10:07.103
Oh, why didn'tl
think of that?

10:07.148 --> 10:09.264
Fargo, turn the machine off.

10:11.444 --> 10:12.980
And that's a stupid question?

10:13.071 --> 10:15.062
I mean, you did
just turn it on, right?

10:15.115 --> 10:17.106
That was an accident.
Jack,
this machine was built

10:17.200 --> 10:18.610
at the height
of the Cold War.

10:18.660 --> 10:20.821
There is no off switch.

10:20.912 --> 10:22.277
Could you cut
the power source?

10:22.372 --> 10:24.454
And risk there's a fail-safe
and it fires immediately?

10:24.541 --> 10:26.532
I take that as a no.
How much time do we have?

10:26.626 --> 10:29.333
ELECTRONIC VOICE:
Weapon will deploy
in 23 hours.

10:29.420 --> 10:30.455
Well, finally
a straight answer.

10:32.006 --> 10:35.248
CARTER: We need to arrange
for transport trucks and
establish evacuation routes.

10:35.301 --> 10:38.293
Make emergency
contingencies for every
location that could be hit.

10:38.346 --> 10:40.632
Yeah, area hospitals
should be prepped
for emergency overflow.

10:40.682 --> 10:43.014
And we'll need to
estimate collateral damage

10:43.101 --> 10:45.387
in and around
the target perimeter.
Good.

10:45.478 --> 10:46.888
You can hear us, right?

10:46.980 --> 10:49.642
Unfortunately.
You're panicking.

10:51.067 --> 10:52.682
We're not panicking,
we're reacting.

10:52.777 --> 10:54.438
You say death ray,
we have a reaction.

10:54.487 --> 10:56.273
You said death ray.

10:56.656 --> 10:58.112
It's a ray, right,

10:58.158 --> 10:59.489
that causes
immediate death?

10:59.576 --> 11:01.908
Yes, it could cause
immediate death.

11:02.370 --> 11:05.862
Could simply blow up
and people here would
immediately die.

11:05.957 --> 11:08.619
It could strike Moscow
and people there would
immediately die.

11:08.668 --> 11:10.704
Then Moscow would retaliate
and people everywhere

11:10.795 --> 11:12.035
would immediate die.

11:12.130 --> 11:14.462
Evacuation's moot.
No place is safe.

11:14.507 --> 11:16.884
Well, you chose
a great time
to be indifferent.

11:17.343 --> 11:19.083
I'm not indifferent,
Shenﬁ.

11:19.179 --> 11:20.544
l'm focused.

11:20.638 --> 11:22.378
We have 24 hours
and we happen to be

11:22.473 --> 11:24.680
in the most advanced
scientific facility
in the world,

11:24.767 --> 11:26.974
housing the largest
supercomputer
in the world,

11:27.020 --> 11:29.978
populated by
the smartest scientists
in the world.

11:30.481 --> 11:31.766
We have plenty of time
to figure this out

11:31.858 --> 11:33.348
as long as
we don't panic.

11:33.443 --> 11:35.604
FARGO: But we've downloaded,
scanned and decrypted

11:35.695 --> 11:38.607
every file, every schematic
and every piece of paper
of every project

11:38.698 --> 11:40.689
ever developed here
and there's nothing.

11:40.783 --> 11:43.399
Well, maybe not
every piece of paper.

11:45.538 --> 11:48.371
HENRY:
This is every piece of paper
I pulled from Fargo's office.

11:48.416 --> 11:51.499
Something here
has to tell us
about that machine.

11:52.212 --> 11:54.624
Come on.
If scientists are so smart,

11:54.714 --> 11:56.705
how come they don't know
anything about penmanship?

11:56.758 --> 11:58.965
Pardon the alliteration,
but which would you prefer,

11:59.052 --> 12:00.633
penmanship or progress?

12:00.720 --> 12:02.221
Tequila.
Scotch.

12:02.597 --> 12:03.962
Really.

12:05.642 --> 12:07.633
What's it?

12:07.727 --> 12:09.934
It What?
|.T.

12:10.021 --> 12:11.602
lt's scribbled at the bottom
of all these pages.

12:11.689 --> 12:14.396
Oh, I don't know maybe,
information technology,

12:14.484 --> 12:17.692
perhaps from the department
from which these
documents originated.

12:17.737 --> 12:19.352
Looks more like
someone's initials.

12:19.405 --> 12:23.239
Well, you are the detective.

12:23.326 --> 12:25.066
Marshal.
Shenﬁ.

12:25.453 --> 12:27.409
That sounds like a demotion.

12:29.582 --> 12:30.617
(CHUCKLES TRIUMPHANTLY)

12:31.125 --> 12:33.081
Hand me some pics.

12:35.546 --> 12:37.832
What's the shiny thing?
Is that a solar flare?

12:38.925 --> 12:42.713
That shiny thing is a mirror.
Now, you do remember
the moon landing, right?

12:43.638 --> 12:44.969
Oh,

12:45.056 --> 12:46.341
do not tell me
that didn't happen.

12:46.432 --> 12:49.139
No, it happened,
but we didn't go to the moon
just to walk.

12:49.227 --> 12:50.592
We put mirrors
all over the moon

12:50.687 --> 12:52.598
to bounce signals
back to the earth,

12:52.689 --> 12:55.431
telescopic images,
satellite communications.

12:55.525 --> 12:56.935
Death rays?

13:04.617 --> 13:05.857
They weaponized the moon.

13:05.952 --> 13:07.442
I mean, they can bounce
a laser off the moon

13:07.495 --> 13:09.281
and wipe out
any target they want.

13:09.372 --> 13:10.452
What, like tanks and stuff?

13:10.540 --> 13:12.656
No. Cities and stuff.

13:14.419 --> 13:16.159
So, you're telling me
while the world watched,

13:16.254 --> 13:18.245
Neil Armstrong take one
small step for man...

13:18.298 --> 13:20.459
NORAD took a giant
leap for themselves.

13:20.550 --> 13:22.290
Well, with the help
from someone at Global.

13:24.470 --> 13:26.552
Someone with
the initials |.T.

13:29.309 --> 13:30.719
|.T.

13:31.144 --> 13:34.511
Oh, Irvin Thatcher.
lt's has to be
Irvin Thatcher.

13:34.605 --> 13:38.097
Irvin Thatcher was
this brilliant scientist
behind MAD.

13:38.151 --> 13:40.813
MADD? Mothers Against
Drunk Driving?

13:40.862 --> 13:43.604
Mutually Assured Destruction.

13:43.948 --> 13:45.688
That MAD.

13:47.160 --> 13:49.321
You said he was
a brilliant scientist.

13:50.246 --> 13:52.988
Was or is?

13:58.546 --> 14:00.161
FRED:
This is easily explained.

14:00.256 --> 14:05.216
The atom nucleus is comprised
of positively-charged protons

14:05.386 --> 14:07.763
and neutrally-charged
neutrons.

14:07.930 --> 14:13.516
When a nucleus
is bombarded by
a neutrally-charged particle,

14:13.686 --> 14:16.063
the result is fission.

14:18.358 --> 14:22.977
You lost me right after,
"This is easily explained."

14:24.030 --> 14:26.692
Okay,
let me try it another way.

14:27.533 --> 14:31.025
Your father is a proton.
Your mother is a neutron.

14:31.496 --> 14:33.828
You are a free radical.

14:34.165 --> 14:36.702
You're caught stealing
CD's in the mall.

14:36.751 --> 14:39.242
You hit your parents
with that news.

14:39.921 --> 14:41.411
What happens?

14:43.007 --> 14:45.214
They go nuclear?
Exactly.

14:46.010 --> 14:47.341
And split.

14:47.678 --> 14:51.262
You think
that I'm the reason
my parents split?

14:51.891 --> 14:54.098
BOTH: No, no, no, no, no.

14:54.727 --> 14:56.888
Zoe? Zoe?

14:56.979 --> 14:58.970
What? I'm doing the job.
I'm helping people.

14:59.065 --> 15:01.556
l'm assisting people.

15:02.860 --> 15:04.236
Fine. Be right back.

15:04.278 --> 15:05.893
Please, carry on.

15:07.740 --> 15:11.278
This is the oppressive jerk
who's all up in your business?

15:12.537 --> 15:14.027
| see you found something
to talk about.

15:14.080 --> 15:16.241
Hi, Sheriff Carter,
nice to meet you.

15:16.332 --> 15:18.197
I'm looking for
a retired scientist.

15:18.251 --> 15:20.082
Swing a cat.

15:20.586 --> 15:23.077
A Dr. Thatcher?
Irvin?

15:23.381 --> 15:25.997
Room 101,
but why do you want...

15:27.427 --> 15:28.416
(SIGHING)

15:28.511 --> 15:30.251
Wait for it.

15:30.596 --> 15:32.257
Hey, room 101,
that would be...

15:32.348 --> 15:34.259
Room 101?
Right this way.

15:38.146 --> 15:39.727
What do you need
him for, Sheriff?

15:39.772 --> 15:43.264
There's a situation.
Even the brainiacs at Global
can't figure it out.

15:43.317 --> 15:46.104
But there is one guy
in town who can

15:46.154 --> 15:49.271
and apparently,
this is the guy.

15:49.449 --> 15:50.859
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

15:51.367 --> 15:53.403
Dr. Thatcher?
This is the guy?

15:53.453 --> 15:57.116
The question remains
fusion or fission?

15:58.291 --> 16:00.907
Fission? Certainly not.

16:01.085 --> 16:04.623
I haven't been fishin'
since I lived on Lake Erie.

16:04.797 --> 16:07.129
You think that's eerie?

16:07.216 --> 16:10.504
How do you explain
quasar energy paradox?

16:12.096 --> 16:14.508
Or baldness among musicians?

16:17.143 --> 16:18.724
This is the guy.

16:21.397 --> 16:24.889
CARTER: Right this way,
Dr. Thatcher.
lRVlN: This way?

16:26.777 --> 16:28.813
Give the doctor some room.

16:30.281 --> 16:32.363
Sir, sir, right this way.

16:35.161 --> 16:37.152
Dr. Thatcher, it's an honor.

16:37.246 --> 16:38.656
l'm Henry Deacon.

16:38.956 --> 16:42.289
This machine of yours,
it's really something.

16:42.335 --> 16:44.701
It's like a riddle
inside an enigma,

16:44.795 --> 16:46.660
wrapped in ten inches
of titanium alloy.

16:46.756 --> 16:48.917
We're assuming it's similar
to other space-based weapons,

16:49.008 --> 16:50.669
using a single-channel
transponder package.

16:50.718 --> 16:53.585
Or maybe
a survivable, low-frequency
communication system.

16:53.679 --> 16:55.010
In which case,
we'd have to reassess

16:55.097 --> 16:58.681
certain aspects
of our approach.
Guys, go easy.

16:58.768 --> 17:00.349
We need launch codes,
Shenﬁ.

17:00.394 --> 17:01.554
And easy is not
going to get it.

17:01.646 --> 17:04.809
Neither is
browbeating the man.
So just give him a minute.

17:13.866 --> 17:15.697
(IRVIN MOANING)

17:25.878 --> 17:27.743
Dr. Thatcher?

17:30.216 --> 17:32.252
We think the controls
are behind this panel.

17:32.343 --> 17:33.799
I just can't figure out
how to get to them.

17:33.886 --> 17:37.219
These locking bolts,
are they some kind of
proprietary threading?

17:37.306 --> 17:40.764
Reverse the hex.
Excuse me?

17:40.893 --> 17:44.101
If you want sex,
reverse the hex.

17:45.898 --> 17:48.765
Sheriff, at any point
when you picked him up,

17:48.859 --> 17:50.724
the car ride,
the long walk down here,

17:50.820 --> 17:53.061
happen to notice
this guy's not all there?

17:53.239 --> 17:54.729
Yeah,
there may have been signs.

17:54.824 --> 17:58.908
Righty loosey,
lefty tighty.

18:01.080 --> 18:02.490
Got it.

18:03.374 --> 18:04.910
Bang-up job.

18:05.585 --> 18:06.574
(CLEARS THROAT)

18:06.669 --> 18:08.409
Reverse the hex.

18:11.424 --> 18:12.709
(CHUCKLING)

18:12.758 --> 18:14.373
The screws recede.

18:17.096 --> 18:18.256
lt's brilliant.

18:26.397 --> 18:30.606
Okay, Dr. Thatcher,
all I need is a code

18:32.278 --> 18:34.519
to suspend
the launch sequence.

18:35.031 --> 18:39.149
Charlie, Tango, Lima.

18:42.038 --> 18:45.781
No, Charlie never
tangoed in Lima.

18:47.168 --> 18:50.285
He's just tired.
Dr. Thatcher, why don't
you take a seat?

18:53.007 --> 18:54.963
Don't give up, okay?

18:55.092 --> 18:59.085
Up, down, up, down.

18:59.639 --> 19:02.551
(SINGING)
The windows on the bus
go up and down

19:02.642 --> 19:05.554
Up and down,
up and down

19:05.645 --> 19:09.388
Any luck?
The windows on the bus
go up and down

19:09.482 --> 19:12.440
Up and down,
up and down

19:14.987 --> 19:16.363
Up and down

19:16.447 --> 19:18.403
The windows on the bus go

19:18.741 --> 19:20.277
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

19:20.785 --> 19:22.275
Why were our kids
sent home from school?

19:22.328 --> 19:23.488
Is there going to be
a missile strike?

19:23.579 --> 19:24.568
Do we need to evacuate?

19:24.664 --> 19:25.870
There's no reason
to panic, folks.

19:25.956 --> 19:28.083
I heard it was a death ray.

19:28.250 --> 19:30.502
That's ridiculous.
That's obviously a rumor.

19:30.586 --> 19:31.996
Started by an idiot.

19:32.046 --> 19:33.627
Who's he?
Is he responsible?

19:33.673 --> 19:36.289
Okay, folks, listen up,
just go on home, okay?

19:36.342 --> 19:39.209
The situation's completely
under control.

19:45.434 --> 19:47.265
It could also be thermal
conductive resistance.

19:47.353 --> 19:49.344
Let me take a look.

19:55.778 --> 19:57.564
Yeah. Looks like they
used the classic formula.

19:57.655 --> 20:00.818
Red for hot, blue for not,
yellow's usually the ground.

20:00.866 --> 20:05.075
So, I guess it's pretty safe
to cut the blue.

20:05.788 --> 20:08.780
What do you think?
ELECTRONIC VOICE: Weapon
will deploy in 20 hours.

20:10.584 --> 20:11.573
Do it.

20:24.306 --> 20:26.558
Launch code
override initiated.

20:27.017 --> 20:28.678
(ALL LAUGHING)
Yes!

20:29.061 --> 20:32.224
Weapon will deploy
in seven hours.

20:33.023 --> 20:34.012
No.

20:35.317 --> 20:38.104
(ALARM BLARING)
Let's not cut
any more wires.

20:47.496 --> 20:51.409
Dr. Thatcher,
I know it's in there.

20:52.084 --> 20:53.949
Just give us a hint.

20:56.046 --> 20:57.377
Gravity.

20:57.423 --> 21:00.130
The natural force
of attraction exerted

21:00.217 --> 21:03.960
by a celestial body
upon objects

21:04.096 --> 21:06.052
at or near its surface.

21:07.933 --> 21:10.891
That's great.
Just be a second.

21:13.439 --> 21:15.145
Look, we have our
best people working on this.

21:15.232 --> 21:17.814
You don't know Nathan,
but he will find a way
to shut it down.

21:17.902 --> 21:21.110
Nothing against
your husband, but...
Ex. Soon to be ex.

21:21.238 --> 21:23.775
But the man with the answers
is sitting right there.

21:23.866 --> 21:25.982
We just need to figure out
how to get them out of him.

21:27.495 --> 21:29.702
What?
What what?

21:29.789 --> 21:31.120
You've got that look
on your face,

21:31.165 --> 21:33.781
like you know something
I should know but
you're not telling me.

21:33.834 --> 21:35.665
Spill.
I can't. lt's classified.

21:35.753 --> 21:36.959
lt's Nathan's turf,

21:37.004 --> 21:38.289
and there is no way
that he is gonna...

21:38.339 --> 21:41.672
Allison, if we don't stop
this thing, there won't be
any turf.

21:43.385 --> 21:44.761
What is it?

21:46.722 --> 21:48.929
Okay. Gravity. Got it.

21:52.311 --> 21:54.302
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

21:57.066 --> 21:58.431
What?

21:58.567 --> 22:00.398
Hey, Allison.

22:02.363 --> 22:03.899
Absolutely not.

22:03.989 --> 22:05.399
That technology
is highly experimental

22:05.491 --> 22:08.153
and far too dangerous
for anyone to...

22:09.286 --> 22:11.277
Carter? Really?

22:12.748 --> 22:15.410
That's just a risk
we may have to take.

22:18.754 --> 22:22.667
So this is basically
a Vulcan mind-meld, right?

22:22.716 --> 22:24.502
Well, the PX-24
allows one person

22:24.593 --> 22:26.333
to probe the consciousness
of another.

22:26.428 --> 22:27.964
In theory, anyway.

22:28.055 --> 22:29.420
In theory?

22:29.515 --> 22:32.052
Well, we haven't
performed a human
test run yet.

22:32.142 --> 22:33.678
Oh.

22:36.230 --> 22:38.186
"In memory of Skippy"?

22:39.733 --> 22:44.193
Oh, he was everyone's
favorite test chimp.

22:46.073 --> 22:47.188
Did he die on this thing?

22:47.241 --> 22:48.230
No.

22:48.868 --> 22:50.950
The autopsy
was inconclusive.

22:51.412 --> 22:53.073
Carter, listen,
I'm not gonna think
any less of you

22:53.163 --> 22:54.869
if you don't
want to do this.

22:59.253 --> 23:01.118
What am I looking for again?

23:01.213 --> 23:03.920
Sequences.
Equations. Codes.
Okay.

23:04.967 --> 23:06.878
Kiss for luck?

23:14.226 --> 23:15.557
Oh, wow.

23:17.146 --> 23:18.556
Last chance
to be a hero, Doc.

23:18.647 --> 23:21.229
Just say the word.

23:22.776 --> 23:24.562
Was worth a shot.

23:30.159 --> 23:32.491
(EXCLAIMING)

23:34.747 --> 23:37.580
(SINGING)
The wheels on the bus
go round and round

23:37.625 --> 23:39.411
Carter, are you okay?

23:40.044 --> 23:42.956
The wheels on the bus
go round and round

23:47.384 --> 23:48.965
IRVIN: Eugenia.

23:57.436 --> 23:58.471
(GROANING)

23:58.562 --> 24:00.644
Okay, I'm stopping this.
No! Keep going.

24:04.944 --> 24:06.400
IRVIN: Stockholm.

24:06.820 --> 24:10.233
Linus Pauling.
Linus Pauling.

24:12.451 --> 24:14.112
Eugenia.
Eugenia.

24:14.161 --> 24:15.401
Eugenia.

24:15.454 --> 24:17.740
Who is Eugenia, Carter?

24:18.248 --> 24:19.237
(GROANING)

24:23.796 --> 24:27.459
IR VIN:
Mutual/y Assured Destruction.

24:30.803 --> 24:31.792
(GROANING)

24:36.600 --> 24:39.808
(EXCLAIMING)

24:39.895 --> 24:41.180
Did you see
how to stop it?

24:42.481 --> 24:43.470
No.

24:44.650 --> 24:46.060
But I saw what happens
if we don't.

24:51.198 --> 24:54.690
Irvin, we're going to go
and see that girl of yours.
Would you like that?

24:56.620 --> 24:59.407
All right.
Don't play coy
with me, okay?

24:59.498 --> 25:00.863
I've been inside
that big brain of yours.

25:00.958 --> 25:02.619
I know how much
you love her.

25:02.668 --> 25:04.875
That doesn't go away,
does it?

25:05.754 --> 25:08.211
Well, I don't think it does.

25:08.799 --> 25:11.632
And I know that
when you're not thinking
about nuclear holocaust,

25:11.677 --> 25:13.884
you're thinking
about Eugenia.

25:16.265 --> 25:18.096
That's what I thought.

25:18.892 --> 25:21.474
Got you with
the nuclear holocaust
thing, didn't I?

25:23.022 --> 25:24.387
I put a trace
on the hot wire.

25:24.481 --> 25:25.937
The power source
leads out the back.

25:26.025 --> 25:27.481
That is where the machine
is vulnerable.

25:27.526 --> 25:30.268
Now, if we can reach that,
then we can get to the guts
of the thing.

25:30.738 --> 25:31.853
I've got a team
in Section Five

25:31.947 --> 25:33.528
working on a laser
bombardment drill

25:33.615 --> 25:35.355
that will bore right through
the titanium shell.

25:35.409 --> 25:36.990
Yeah, unfortunately
your guys in Section Four

25:37.036 --> 25:40.654
tell me it's not titanium,
it's zirconium carbonite,
which is...

25:40.706 --> 25:41.786
Impenetrable.

25:41.874 --> 25:46.868
But, I believe
we can get there
from here

25:46.962 --> 25:48.668
through the base
of the machine.

25:48.714 --> 25:50.250
If we tunnel down,
under and up,

25:50.340 --> 25:53.377
we'll be directly
behind it and then
I think we've got a shot.

25:53.469 --> 25:55.300
Tell Fargo to give you
anything you need.

25:55.387 --> 25:57.878
And not to touch
anything you don't.

26:00.017 --> 26:02.929
Bad news, good news.
We didn't get anything
from Thatcher,

26:03.020 --> 26:04.851
but Carter wasn't hurt
in the process.

26:04.897 --> 26:06.512
And the good news?

26:08.358 --> 26:10.394
There you go, buddy.
Take a seat.

26:10.736 --> 26:15.070
I'll go look for Eugenia
and you enjoy the view
with a room.

26:16.200 --> 26:17.565
Where is that?

26:22.289 --> 26:23.745
IRVIN: Stockholm.

26:24.083 --> 26:25.573
Linus Pauling.

26:26.752 --> 26:30.415
Royal Palace.
Stockholm. Sweden.

26:32.216 --> 26:33.581
How do you know that?

26:33.634 --> 26:35.841
I don't know. I was there.

26:35.928 --> 26:37.418
VVhen?
Recently.

26:38.138 --> 26:40.424
Do you know
where Eugenia is?

26:40.474 --> 26:42.089
She's not to be disturbed.

26:42.184 --> 26:43.424
Her words, not mine.

26:43.519 --> 26:44.759
Come on. Come on.

26:48.440 --> 26:50.226
This is her.

26:52.236 --> 26:53.351
Eugenia?

26:53.445 --> 26:55.106
Eugenia, it's Zoe.

26:55.864 --> 26:58.116
Has she done
something wrong?
No, no.

26:58.158 --> 27:00.274
Eugenia, it's Sheriff Carter.
I need to talk to you.

27:00.327 --> 27:02.864
Is there something
I should know?
No.

27:03.163 --> 27:05.028
There is, isn't there?

27:07.251 --> 27:11.369
Actually, yeah, yeah.
That crack I made about
you being a delinquent?

27:11.672 --> 27:13.913
Yeah.
Didn't mean it.

27:14.466 --> 27:16.002
You're my girl.

27:17.219 --> 27:19.835
It's really bad, isn't it?
No.

27:20.764 --> 27:22.265
Eugenia!
Eugenia!

27:29.982 --> 27:30.971
Eugenia?

27:32.109 --> 27:33.098
Eugenia?

27:37.531 --> 27:39.021
Eugenia?

27:45.998 --> 27:47.454
Come in, Jo.

27:48.500 --> 27:49.489
Where are you, Jo?

27:49.877 --> 27:51.663
Come on, Jo.
Talk to us.

27:51.753 --> 27:54.005
We all live here.
We have a right to know
what's going on.

27:54.089 --> 27:55.590
What is the trajectory
of the weapon?

27:55.674 --> 27:57.460
Is there a sea-based
boost phase intercept?

27:57.509 --> 27:59.886
BOTH:
Have the launch protocols
been initiated?

27:59.970 --> 28:01.926
Don't know. Don't know.

28:02.014 --> 28:03.504
Don't know.

28:03.557 --> 28:04.888
MAN: What do you know?
Go home.

28:04.975 --> 28:07.387
We've got everything
under control.

28:07.686 --> 28:09.551
(WHIRRING)

28:10.355 --> 28:11.765
WOMAN: What is that?

28:14.943 --> 28:16.194
Except for that.

28:21.325 --> 28:22.440
Zoe, think.
Did she say anything

28:22.534 --> 28:24.035
about going anywhere,
doing anything?

28:24.119 --> 28:25.199
Not that I remember.

28:25.287 --> 28:27.699
How about family?
Did she ask the kids
to pick her up or something?

28:27.748 --> 28:29.363
It never came up, okay?
Where is that?

28:30.500 --> 28:34.084
The MENSA Think-Off?
Yeah, I seriously doubt
you can compete.

28:34.171 --> 28:36.207
No, the sundial,
where is that?

28:36.298 --> 28:37.788
Copernicus Park.
I can see...

28:37.883 --> 28:40.875
It's on the south side
of the distilled water tower.
Come on.

28:40.969 --> 28:42.084
That's where
I'll find my girl.

28:42.179 --> 28:43.589
I thought I was your girl.

28:44.056 --> 28:45.796
Wait, that sounded weird.

28:47.017 --> 28:49.053
(DRILLING)

28:51.688 --> 28:53.019
Henry...

28:56.401 --> 28:58.232
Henry, how's it...

28:59.404 --> 29:01.110
Henry,
how's the drilling going?

29:01.198 --> 29:04.406
HENRY: This laser bombardment
drill cuts through quartz
like butter!

29:04.451 --> 29:07.864
I should be done drilling
in what, five hours.

29:08.247 --> 29:11.489
ELECTRONIC VOICE:
Weapon will deploy
in four hours.

29:12.584 --> 29:14.415
Drill faster.
Yeah.

29:21.426 --> 29:23.758
Oh, my God, Eugenia.
What...

29:23.887 --> 29:26.003
What are you doing?
How did you even get here?

29:26.098 --> 29:30.262
Henry souped up my chair.
I can go 50 miles
between charges.

29:30.727 --> 29:32.718
So, why have I been
pushing you around all day?

29:32.771 --> 29:34.807
I wanted you to feel good
about yourself,

29:34.898 --> 29:36.854
like you were assisting.

29:37.192 --> 29:39.478
Fine.
I didn't hate the company.

29:47.452 --> 29:49.488
Dad, are you okay?

29:56.295 --> 29:58.786
IRVIN: Eugenia.

30:01.425 --> 30:03.507
Dad, what the hell
are you doing?

30:05.429 --> 30:07.340
Why did you do that?

30:08.849 --> 30:10.339
I'm not sure.

30:10.684 --> 30:13.300
Mind your own business, Zoe.

30:14.146 --> 30:15.352
Sorry.

30:15.814 --> 30:18.430
Your anniversary.
Our anniversary.

30:19.192 --> 30:22.525
Anniversary? Of what?
You and me.

30:22.696 --> 30:24.277
Him, Thatcher.

30:24.323 --> 30:25.688
Anniversary?

30:26.074 --> 30:27.359
He never even proposed.

30:28.452 --> 30:29.658
Yes, he did.

30:30.620 --> 30:31.700
I saw it.

30:32.164 --> 30:33.620
Trust me.
Never happened.

30:35.083 --> 30:36.994
ls dementia contagious?

30:37.836 --> 30:41.545
No, okay,
in his mind he proposed.

30:41.631 --> 30:44.338
I mean right here.
That's why you come here.

30:46.053 --> 30:50.763
I come here
for lunch every day.

30:51.725 --> 30:54.011
This is where we first met.

30:56.021 --> 31:00.014
We'd sit and look at the sky.

31:00.233 --> 31:03.441
He told me
how the stars shined,

31:03.695 --> 31:06.402
how the planets revolved
around the sun,

31:08.033 --> 31:10.524
how his universe
revolved around me.

31:12.412 --> 31:16.872
And then his universe
came crashing down
and mine with it.

31:19.711 --> 31:21.247
What happened?

31:21.380 --> 31:24.747
We were going to
get married in Stockholm

31:24.841 --> 31:26.832
after Irvin won the prize.

31:27.010 --> 31:29.092
The Nobel Prize?

31:29.179 --> 31:32.342
No one imagined Linus Pauling
would win a second Nobel.

31:32.391 --> 31:34.552
It was devastating to Irvin.

31:34.726 --> 31:38.639
He had a complete
mental break the day
of the announcement,

31:39.564 --> 31:42.055
the day he was
going to propose.

31:42.150 --> 31:44.812
The day I lost
the love of my life.

31:46.238 --> 31:48.900
The picture,
the virtual Stockholm.

31:49.032 --> 31:52.900
You must think
I'm a fool pining over
a love that's gone.

31:53.578 --> 31:55.079
It's not gone.

31:55.122 --> 31:57.738
We just have to pick up
where we left off.

31:58.542 --> 32:00.032
Did I say we?

32:03.130 --> 32:04.620
Sorry.

32:06.842 --> 32:09.879
ELECTRONIC VOICE:
Weapon will deploy
in three hours.

32:09.928 --> 32:11.259
Well, there's got to
be something.

32:11.304 --> 32:14.432
I mean, use explosives
to blast through the rest
of the bedrock.

32:14.474 --> 32:17.466
This machine was programmed
as a second-strike
dead man's weapon.

32:17.561 --> 32:19.677
Any kind of explosion and...

32:19.771 --> 32:22.854
I cannot believe
we built this thing
to protect ourselves.

32:22.941 --> 32:24.681
I'm gonna have to
put a call in to the DOD.

32:24.776 --> 32:25.936
You can't.
I have to.

32:26.027 --> 32:29.235
You can't.
I think that they'll notice
if we start World War III.

32:29.281 --> 32:31.112
Allison, think about it.

32:31.408 --> 32:33.273
What are you going to say,
we may accidentally
blow up Moscow,

32:33.326 --> 32:35.362
Beijing, Pyongyang
and Stockholm?

32:35.454 --> 32:37.615
Okay, I know how fond
you are of Stockholm, Nathan,

32:37.706 --> 32:39.071
but this is bigger than you.

32:39.124 --> 32:40.910
If you tell them
that we can't stop it,

32:40.959 --> 32:42.244
they're gonna try
and stop it.

32:42.294 --> 32:43.579
They'll nuke us and...
And I know.

32:43.628 --> 32:46.085
Any kind of explosion
can trigger the device.
I get it.

32:46.131 --> 32:47.496
But we're running
out of options.

32:47.591 --> 32:50.048
I beg to differ.
I'm gonna need to borrow
your Nobel.

32:51.970 --> 32:53.050
It was open.

32:53.305 --> 32:55.261
Oh. Sorry.

32:55.765 --> 32:57.892
What in the hell
are you doing?

32:57.976 --> 33:00.388
Going to party
like it's 1962.

33:04.483 --> 33:06.269
I miss Sheriff Cobb.

33:12.532 --> 33:14.648
(AUDIENCE CLAPPING)

33:15.285 --> 33:16.821
You should wear
that dress more often.

33:16.912 --> 33:18.868
Do you think this will work?
Works for me.

33:20.165 --> 33:21.200
Let's hope so.

33:21.958 --> 33:23.334
Oh, Sheriff.

33:23.502 --> 33:24.833
When a light bulb
goes off in your head,

33:24.878 --> 33:26.834
what are we talking,
15, 20 watts?

33:28.215 --> 33:29.955
You have a better idea,
I'd love to hear it.

33:30.008 --> 33:32.215
No? Yeah.
Better get started.

33:38.183 --> 33:40.390
Jo, wow, you look...

33:40.477 --> 33:43.765
No, you look the other way.
NA THAN: Ladies and gentlemen,
and distinguished colleagues,

33:43.855 --> 33:45.356
welcome to Stockholm.

33:45.690 --> 33:48.352
Robert Oppenheimer
famously said,

33:48.401 --> 33:52.394
"The atomic bomb
made the prospect
of future war unendurable."

33:52.864 --> 33:55.196
One man never forgot
those words,

33:55.283 --> 33:57.569
the man we welcome
among us today,

33:57.661 --> 34:00.528
the man whom
the Nobel Committee
of the NonNegian parliament

34:00.580 --> 34:02.741
has selected
for this year's award
of the Nobel Prize,

34:02.832 --> 34:05.369
Dr. Irvin Horatio Thatcher.

